{"name": "camshell", "metadata": {"name": "camshell", "version": "0.1.0", "classifiers": ["License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13"], "home_page": null, "license": "MIT", "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["asciimatics", "click", "opencv-python"], "summary": "A simple tool to stream camera in shell.", "upload_time": 1734711823}, "documentation": ["# CamShell\n\nCamShell, A simple way to stream a camera as ASCII art directly in a terminal.\n\n\n## Installation\n\nUsing pip:\n\n```bash\npip install camshell\n```\n\n## How to Use\n\nCLI Usage:\n\nAfter installation, you can run the `camshell` command-line tool or by providing\nthe device id.\n\n```bash\n# Run the default device\ncamshell\n\n# Or run by device-id\ncamshell 1\n\n# Or a device path specifically\ncamshell /dev/video3\n```\n\n## Python API Usage\n\nIf you\u2019d like to use XDisplay in your Python code, here\u2019s how:\n\n```python\nfrom camshell.xdisplay import XDisplay as CamShellDisplay\n\n# simply call:\ndevice_id = \"/dev/video0\"\nCamShellDisplay.start(device_id)\n```\n\nRun on a custom screen\n\n```python\nfrom asciimatics.screen import Screen\nfrom camshell.xdisplay import XDisplay as CamShellDisplay\n\nwith XDisplay(cap_id=\"/dev/video0\") as display:\n    Screen.wrapper(display.run)\n```\n\n"], "modules": [{"name": "camshell", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "camshell.cli", "xref": {"fqname": "camshell.cli.cli", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "camshell.cli", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "camshell.cli.cli", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "cap_id", "type": {"name": "str | None", "xref": null, "params": null}, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["A Simple CLI to display video feed in terminal.\n\nArguments:\ncap_id -- Camera ID or path to video device."]}], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name